  "prompt": "Will PHP become obsolete in near future?",
  "response": "PHP is unlikely to become obsolete in the near future. Here are some reasons:\n\n1. Current Usage\n- Still powers around 77% of websites, including major platforms like WordPress, Facebook, and Wikipedia\n- Large existing codebase and legacy systems\n- Continues to evolve with modern features\n\n2. Ongoing Development\n- PHP 8.x series with improved performance and features\n- Active community and regular updates\n- Continuous improvements in language design\n\n3. Strong Ecosystem\n- Frameworks like Laravel, Symfony, and CodeIgniter\n- Extensive libraries and packages\n- Mature development tools and resources\n\n4. Server-Side Advantages\n- Easy to learn\n- Low hosting costs\n- Quick development\n- Good performance with recent versions\n\n5. Enterprise Adoption\n- Many large organizations still use PHP\n- Stable and reliable for web development\n\n6. Integration Capabilities\n- Works well with databases\n- Supports multiple platforms\n- Compatible with various web technologies\n\nChallenges:\n- Competition from Node.js, Python, and other languages\n- Need for continuous modernization\n- Performance compared to some newer technologies\n\nWhile PHP might decline in popularity, it's not likely to become completely obsolete in the near future. It will likely continue to evolve and maintain its significance in web development.",
